    <bioghist>
      <head>Historical Note</head>
      <p>The Chicago Lawn Union Church was a mission church formed in 1897 to support the religious
        lives of those in the, at the time, largely farming community of the Chicago Lawn
        neighborhood. Members of that mission church eventually organized the Chicago Lawn
        Congregational Church in 1902. Rev. Alexander Monroe was the first minister of the newly
        established church. At first the congregation met at the Lawn Club Hall. Within two years of
        the church's formation, a simple two-story frame church was built near the intersections of
        62nd Place and South Saint Louis Avenue.</p>
      <p>Land for a new church building was donated to the church by Vandelia Thomas (neé Varnum),
        wife of the late Rev. Hiram Washington Thomas, who had founded the Unitarian Peoples Church
        of Chicago. In honor of the donation of land, the name of the church was changed to Hiram W.
        Thomas Memorial Congregational Church in 1912. The new church building was constructed at
        the corner of 64th Place and South Homan Avenue and it was completed in 1917. Following
        Vandelia's death in 1923, the name of the church was changed again to Thomas Memorial Church
        to honor both Vandelia and Hiram.</p>
      <p>In 1950, the church was remodeled and renovated and a new educational wing was added to the
        church. The church joined with the United Church of Christ following the formation of the
        denomination in 1957. The church officially dissolved in early 2000 owing to decreased
        membership. The church building remains as an active church within the Chicago Lawn
        community.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent>
      <head>Scope and Contents</head>
      <p>This collection contains the vital membership records of the Thomas Memorial Congregational
        Church as well as the earliest meeting minutes for the church. The collection includes
        meeting minutes, baptismal records, membership records and membership lists, marriage
        records, necrologies, and a 1967 annual report.</p>
    </scopecontent>
    <arrangement>
      <head>Arrangement</head>
      <p>Materials in this collection have been arranged in chronological order by start date.</p>
    </arrangement>
